Including Plots

You can also embed plots, for example:

Note that the echo = FALSE parameter was added to the code chunk to prevent printing of the R code that generated the plot.

data(arbuthnot)

Data Visualization:

ggplot(data = arbuthnot, aes(x = year, y = girls)) + geom_point()

The function ggplot() builds the plot and the arguments used are data(data set name), aes(x and y axis). Then you need to add a layer to the blank ggplot() with + geom_point() aka scatterplot

*To make a line graph instead use + geom_line()

ggplot(data = arbuthnot, aes(x = year, y = girls)) + geom_line()

Exercise 2

The line graph above shows that, overall, the number of girls baptized in London increased from 1629 to 1710.

Adding a New Variable to the Data Frame

To calculate the total number of baptisms each year, add the vector for boys to the vector for girls.

arbuthnot <- arbuthnot %>% 
  mutate(total = boys + girls)

The %>% is the piping operator that takes the output of the previous expression and “pipes it” into the first argument of the next expression arbuthnot %>% piping into the next expression

I could have used: mutate(arbuthnot, total = boys + girls)

ggplot(data = arbuthnot, aes(x = year, y = total)) + geom_line()

To find the boy to girl ratio for the whole column save the ratio calculation for each row into a new variable in the table

Exercise 3

arbuthnot <- arbuthnot %>% mutate(boys_ratio = boys / total)
ggplot(data = arbuthnot, aes(x = year, y= boys_ratio)) + geom_line()

arbuthnot <- arbuthnot %>% mutate(more_boys = boys > girls)

This new variable contains a true or false value called logical data

More Practice

Exercise 4

The years on the present data set are from 1940-2002. The dimensions of the data set are x = years, y = number of boy births, number of girl births. The variable names are year, boy, girl.

Exercise 5

How do these counts compare to Arbuthnot’s? Are they of a similar magnitude?

The number of births recorded in London from 1629-1710 were lower than the recorded births in the US from 1940-2002. The magnitude for present births are much higher.

present <- present %>% mutate(total = boys + girls) 
ggplot() + geom_line(data = arbuthnot, aes(x = year, y = total), color = "blue") + geom_line(data = present, aes(x = year, y = total), color = "red")

Exercise 6

present <- present %>% mutate(boys_ratio = boys / total)
ggplot() + geom_line(data = arbuthnot, aes(x = year, y = boys_ratio), color = "blue") + geom_line(data = present, aes(x = year, y = boys_ratio), color = "red")

The ratio of boys being born to girls being born drops and Arbuthnot’s observation of boys being in greater proportion does not hold up in the present US.
